  "summary": "Roger and Frankie discuss Henry’s morphine addiction and speculate that he may be receiving treatment from Dr. Nicholson, a Canadian who runs a nearby institution for mental illness and drug addiction. They decide to keep the addiction a secret from Sylvia to avoid burdening her and to encourage Henry to seek professional help. During a conversation, Sylvia mentions the Nicholsons, expressing a strong dislike for Dr. Nicholson despite noting his handsomeness, and describes Moira Nicholson as a captivating woman.\n\nFrankie decides to conduct experiments to determine if Roger is responsible for the morphine poisoning of Bobby, noting that Roger could have easily obtained the drug. Her plan is to establish Roger's whereabouts on the 16th and observe his reaction to a photograph of the deceased man. At dinner, Frankie subtly asks Roger if he was at Claridge's on the 16th; however, Sylvia intervenes, stating that Roger was home for a party, which leads Frankie to conclude that Roger was not in Wales on the day of the poisoning.\n\nFrankie then steers the conversation toward the man who fell off a cliff in Machabert. Roger admits he was present at the scene until the police arrived but claims he left for London the morning after the tragedy. When Frankie presents a newspaper clipping of the deceased to the group, Sylvia notes that the man in the photo resembles Allen Castles, a sentiment Roger partially agrees with. Despite these inquiries, Frankie remains puzzled as the group's reactions appear natural.",
